711707f-a.text:
23rd Street, north side, west from Ninth Avenue. At right is the original London Terrace, a row of cottages and apartment houses built in 1845 by Bishop Clement C. Moore, author of "The Night before Christmas". These houses were modeled on similar structures popular in London at the time, and for many years constituted a very fashionable address. They were demolished in 1929 and 1930, and replaced by a series of large, modern apartment houses which retain the name London Terrace.

About 1927.

Price Studios, Inc.
Neg.  #1134

711711f-a.text:
Rosae Crucis Club, 361 West 23rd Street, north side, just east of Ninth Avenue. This was originally the home of the famous theatrical producer James Fisk. After his assassination by Howard S. Stokes, the house was acquired by Lilly Langtry, the famous English actress.
[January 26, crossed out] 1928.
P. L. Sperr.

711712f-a.text:
361-363 West 23rd Street, north side, east of Ninth Avenue. This house was the residence of the theatrical producer James Fisk; after his assassination, it was owned by the famous actress Lilly Langtry. It is now the Rosae Crucis Club, and will by 1935 be demolished.
About 1925.
